text: I'm so tired of people pretending they're too smart/Christian/well-read, or know too much about either BDSM, or what constitutes "mommy porn" to give the book or the movie a chance to be exactly what it is...a guilty pleasure. I've watched soap operas for most of my life, and I don't take them a bit seriously, I can go through romance novels just as quickly as I can read the classics, and I can still claim an IQ of well above 145.Â  The books weren't porn, if you want to read that, go pick up Wifey by Judy Blume, or something by Erica Jong. Those were around in the 70's and far more explicit, and no one blinked an eye. The movie will not be porn because the books weren't.Â  There was nothing even close to rape in the books, so I don't know where that's coming from. The books aren't about her signing a contract and becoming a submissive to him...they are about her NOT doing it...and changing HIM. Therefore, this is a love story, not a BDSM story.Â  So, while all of you who think you are too intelligent to go watch this are enjoying the next Superman, Spiderman, Ironman, or whatever mindless movie full of explosions is playing at the theater next door, I will be enjoying MY guilty pleasure, too. And to the person who posted that "it's gray, not grey, you idiots," you are WRONG. In the US, it's spelled gray, in England, it's spelled grey...and since his last name is Grey, it makes absolutely no difference, a surname is spelled how it's spelled! (You idiot). Sorry, but that was well-deserved.

text: You know what? I'm not really into BDSM. Not my thing. BUT...I am watching this phenomenon knock people for a loop because it's MAKING people talk. It's bringing everyone's judgments to the surface like a doctor lancing a festering boil. We have GOT to quit being so dang prudish about sex, no matter what "flavor" rocks your boat. Being a writer myself AND being a female, I couldn't resist a peek at the books, to say nothing of the trailers. This is going to be a LOT more entertaining for me than the "Twilight" series upon which "Fifty Shades" is based. As for those who think this is "porn," I wonder. Have you actually watched porn? Much of it, even the stuff written for women, is poorly acted, and there are no complicated emotional dynamics. "Fifty Shades" on the other hand, gives us a taste of the kind of dynamics involved between Christian and Anastasia--and if the trailer is any indication, it's going to be one hell of a ride. And in the end, come on. It's a STORY. And it is clearly a story that is doing what it's supposed to do: make people sit up, take notice and talk about it, for good or ill. "Fifty Shades" NEEDS to be shocking in order to shake us out of our centuries-long puritanical prudery. Does this mean I am going to go around talking about my sex life with everyone? No. There's a time and a place, sure. However, and it is a BIG however: "Fifty Shades" promotes frank talk about sex in general, which is what this country still needs, whether or not one is into BDSM. So bring it on! About time we brought this subject out in the open so we can release the toxicity.

text: Gonna see this movie with a friend. She loves the books, me, I never read it. I actually read excerpts but it wasn't enough to intrigue me. I actually found myself laughing while reading. I know this movie and books have been stirring up controversy about healthy relationships, and the BDSM community. About the relationship, people need to remember it's all fictional. Just like any relationship in romantic novels, it's fictional. Doesn't matter if it's an erotic novel or a teen romance novel or whatever romance novel, it's fictional. A fantasy to enjoy, even if others think the fantasy is crap. To each their own. But if people are looking for their own Christian Grey, they need to be pulled back down to earth cuz reality is totally different. Now if people want to experiment with BDSM, I suggest that they actually do their proper research about BDSM (consent, limits, etc.) instead of relying on ideas coming from a fictional book. That way, people are not being hurt nor killed.  With all that said, I'm actually excited to see the movie. I'm ready to giggle at the awkward moments and see other viewer's reactions!
